
                                            Melville Koppies, in the Johannesburg suburb, is often used for expression of religion and faith – causing a debate over animal abuse versus practising own beliefs.
                                         JOHANNESBURG - PhD Candidate at Wits Centre for Diversity Studies Scott Burnett says people are very much used to a particular way of being which is conditioned by the country’s racially divided history. Melville Koppies, in the Johannesburg suburb, is often used for expression of religion and faith – causing a debate over animal abuse versus practising own beliefs. Burnett says lawfully, one can slaughter an animal but needs to obtain permission from the municipality firstly. Listen to the audio above for more.